Title: Deep End
Author: Ali Hazelwood
My Review:
Read this on a whim for a flight. I wasn't planning on reading this book because I had given up on Ali Hazelwood. I loved The Love Hypothesis, but then I really disliked the steminist novels that she put out because I felt like they were recycled and then I never picked up another one of her books. But, I was inspired to pick this one up, because I was a swimmer for 15 years of my life and I'm glad I did!

I really loved this book, with the emphasis on mental health and how that can affect Scarlett's diving. I also liked how they explored the dom/sub stuff with the acknowledgment on feminism and the control it brings. I'm not typically a fan of that stuff, but I liked how it was represented with the constant check ins from Luk, it felt caring and consensual which sometimes other books lack.

Loved this one! I think it's bringing me out of my reading slump. (I haven't read a book in 3 months)
Genre: No ISBN

Title: Either/Or
Author: Elif Batuman
My Review:
Going into this book I did not know it was a sequel. It doesn't even say that it is on Goodreads. I didn't realize that until I was about a quarter of the way through and was confused why they were throwing all these characters at us, as if we were supposed to know them already. (Turns out we were supposed to know them already lmao) Even without the background, I think I have a good understanding of how the first book ended up going, with her current obsession with Ivan.

I thought this was a really interesting book with a very unique main character who was both relatable and unrelatable. Clearly Selin was incredibly smart, but lack the social understanding of lots of things. I probably didn't understand as much of the book as I would've liked, since I have no knowledge of any of the Russian literature that was referenced in the novel, but I still enjoyed it.

Title: Vengeful (Villains, #2)
Author: Victoria E. Schwab
My Review:
Edit October 2024:
So I just did a reread of the two Villains books in the past couple months and I had totally forgotten what happened in this book! Rereading my old review everything is still true. Except now we know that there will be a third one!

OG Review June 2021:
Wow this was a whirlwind. I am in love with Victor Vale and it isn't surprising. He's such a fascinating character and impossible not to love. I found out recently that there is possibly a third book in this Villians world and you better believe I will be the first person to pre-order that book when it comes out.

I love that we were able to find out so much more about Eli's history and backstory and I thought that Marella's character was so fascinating.

I think I'm in shock and denial that Eli died. I really wanted it to be a battle of wit and have Victor figure something out and kill Eli but it happened to be that crazy scientist instead. And the scientist, I can't even remember his name was so insignificant it almost seems unfair. But I really like that Sydney was the one who pulled the trigger to finish Eli off since Victor wasn't the one able to do it.

I'm sad that Victor kinda left Sydney and Mitch in the dust and walked away. I think that Sydney must be the key to saving him since she was the one who revived him in the first place. Like maybe they kill Victor and Sydney can bring him back fixed.

Also I've always wondered what would happen if Eli was decapitated. Does his head grow a new body, or does his body grow a new head. That would've been interesting to explore.

I love this book so much! This Villians universe is definitely one of my favorites.

Title: Six of Crows (Six of Crows, #1)
Author: Leigh Bardugo
My Review:
WOW!

This book is what I have been looking for for ages.

I love Kaz and Inej, they're my favorite characters.

Also, actual badass characters who kill. Not fake assassins or criminal YA characters who are afraid of killing when it needs to be done. Real Killers. YESSSSSSSSSSSSSSS

Edit April 15, 2021:

Wow, my fourth reread of Six Of Crows. Every time it blows me away. I thought, maybe I could give this book a proper review. (Though none of my reviews are ever proper)

This is hands down my favorite book of all time. Yes. My favorite book of all time.
I'm rereading it now for the Shadow and Bone TV show coming out on April 23, 2021.

Once again, I'm shocked by how beautiful Bardugo's writing is. The way it flows and melds together is beautiful. Every single word keeps my eyes glued to the page. Even though it's my fourth time reading it, it always feels like it's my first.

Kaz Brekker is the ultimate guy. He's dark and brooding and insane, but somehow realistic. I love how Bardugo creates these characters that are so strong and powerful, but all of them have incredibly deep flaws that keep them grounded. I'll never get tired of this book. Never. It's amazing and I'm so glad to have read it.

Edit May 7, 2024:
This is my 5th time reading this book because I bought the special LitJoy Crate edition with annotations written by Bardugo herself. I loved reading this because it allowed me to see all her background thoughts of a lot of scenes.

Title: Vicious (Villains, #1)
Author: Victoria E. Schwab
My Review:
I love how V.E. Schwab tells her stories weaving back and forth between the past and the present. Filling in gaps in such an artistic way keeping my eyes glued to the page. (Of course I don't know if that's always her MO since this is only the second book I've read of hers. The first being the Invisible Life Of Addie LaRue.)

I love Victor's character! I like how he's so morally gray and so fixed on his revenge. I like the world she created with EOs and Sydney's character was so great too.

I'm so lucky that I get to now read the sequel and do not have to wait 5 years to read it like the original people who read this book.

I can't wait to see what Victor Vale is up to next!

Title: Jade City (The Green Bone Saga, #1)
Author: Fonda Lee
My Review:
I really liked this book. I was buddy reading this with my boyfriend and he's probably the only reason why I finished this book. It was quite slow in some places and didn't really start to get interesting until the midway point.

I've never read or watched anything like it. I don't have an interest in gang or mafia stories so I've never seen the godfather or any of the other content the author said she was inspired by. Thus, the story felt incredibly fresh and exciting to someone who's not familiar with those trope. I think I would want to continue reading the books, but it might take some time.

Overall the characters are really well written and I like the exploration the the world and it's culture. The jade powers and Green Bones are so creative. I like that They killed Lan. It makes me feel like no character is safe from death going forward.

My only complaint is that I don't LOVE any characters yet. And as a very character driven person, I hope to love a character in the coming books.

Title: King of Pride (Kings of Sin, #2)
Author: Ana Huang
My Review:
Honestly my least favorite of the Ana Huang books so far. I liked Kai's personality but Isa seemed too much like "I'm not like other girls." As someone who had purple hair for a long time, and owns a pet snake I was excited to read this book. That she would actually have a unique personality different from other girls. That she could actually be your normal everyday girl.

What was the reason for making it so she was actually the daughter of a family that still was worth hundreds of millions of dollars? Was that supposed to make her relatable? She didn't need to have that background. Oh no boo her she chooses to live like a normal person out of principle but actually is a trust fund baby. And then uses all her connections to land her job working for Alessandra doing who knows what.

I liked Twisted Hate the most out of all of Ana Huang's books because it was between a med student and a law student. I know that this series is all super rich dudes, but billionaire romances are so common and there are already so many. I will probably still keep reading her books but I liked when she had more unique story lines.

Title: The Chalice of the Gods (Percy Jackson and the Olympians: The Senior Year Adventures #1)
Author: Rick Riordan
My Review:
Reading this was a rollercoaster of nostalgia and emotion for me. I was extremely hesitant to read this book originally. I had sworn it off because I sorta feel like it's a cash grab, or Rick Riordan is just bored and doesn't know what to do. I'm not sure I disagree with that, but I'll tell you my thoughts and feelings of the actual novel.

I LOVE Percy Jackson. When I say that I don't mean it lightly. Growing up through the end of elementary school and early high school, I read, and reread all the major 10 books in the series. (PJO and HOO) Well, the last 3 books of HOO I had to wait in anticipation yearly, and read on the days it came out. I was part of online fandom communities, and discussion boards. This series was my childhood, the way Harry Potter was for a lot of millennials. And I didn't fall off after that either. I still read all Magnus Chase Books and Trials of Apollo. Then during the pandemic, I reread all of PJO and HOO again! Safe to say I'm a big fan and it's really important to me.

This book did NOT disappoint me. The writing felt timeless and goofy. It felt like I was reading a continuation of Percy as a senior in high school, although maybe his tone is slightly immature for a senior in high school, but I understand the book is still considered middle grade so that could be it. I liked seeing the original trio back together again, although more of Annabeth would've been nice.

The book had a simple formula of the Percy Jackson books, though there wasn't really any fighting or monsters in it. I kinda liked that. Like, give Percy a break, he's been through enough. I can see that this is going to be book 1/3 in the series probably, and I'll pick up the rest to read too. I liked the book, and it hit the nostalgia spots in a good way.

Author: Chloe Gong
My Review:
I've loved all previous 3 books in the Secrets of Shanghai world, but this finale was definitely the weakest in my opinion. It took me a long time to get through the book, especially the beginning. I was stuck on the first 150 pages for well over a month and it took me sitting in a metal chamber in the sky to then push through and get through the entire book.

Of course, once I got into the flow of the story, Gong's writing is very easy to read and engaging. I really love all the characters a lot, and she does a great job with having such a large cast of characters. However, I disliked how the ending was perfectly tied up in a bow. It would have been much more compelling and realistic if there was anyone who died or any tragedy. It seemed a little unbelievable how everything got resolved in the end.

I thought the twist with Silas was good but then he actually was good and was just double triple crossing and that was supposed to be sweet but where is the flavor. Idk there just could've been more.

I still enjoyed reading the story though, 3.5 stars.

Title: Good Girl Complex (Avalon Bay, #1)
Author: Elle Kennedy
My Review:
Easy to read candy book although I only gave it three stars. I feel like this book made Mac a total girl boss. So, she's from an ultra rich family, but is still a self made millionaire. I was excited at first because I thought she knew how to code or something bc the reason why she made money is a social media platform. But, no, it was just and idea. That means she's really not self-made at all because how can you get read coders to take your business idea seriously if you don't have the family clout and capital in order to hire them.

It really wouldn't have been that much harder to change that about her but I guess being a girl who codes isn't that sexy. (it really could be tho) Additionally, one of the reasons why Preston is so bad is because he doesn't take her business venture seriously and once he actually found out that she made money for it he hated it. And she broke up with him. But, later when Cooper feels emasculated that Mac has all this money (which she is self-made) and he gets mad at her about it, that's not a total red flag. Like, realistic, yes, but also like you don't need him.

Men suck. Most of them can't handle it when their girl is more successful than them, and that was a huge plot line with the sexism of her family and her ex boyfriend. Then, actually have a real conversation with Cooper about it where he realizes it's okay rather than brushing it under the rug. Fr. Girl, you don't really need him. What is Cooper giving her that she can't have on her own. Just kinda ticked me off. Like we get it that tattooed bad boy who's masculine is so hot. Whatever, sure having an alpha guy is popular in romance books. But then it's a hard balance when the whole point is that Mac needs to be independent from her ex and family bc they're sexist.

Title: Immortal Longings (Flesh and False Gods, #1)
Author: Chloe Gong
My Review:
I think I liked this more than some other people. I totally understand some of the criticisms this book has gotten. It really still feels YA, not adult. Due to the success of Chloe's previous books, she hasn't really improved as a writer and some of the styling feels repetitive. However, I still felt the book to be fast paced enough and overall felt intrigued and wanted to continue reading.

The fantasy aspect seems a little weak and she could have gone more in depth on the ethics and morals of jumping. I disagree with some of the criticisms about how jumping and using other bodies where there is no consent. I think that argument doesn't really make sense because in this fantasy world jumping is a thing and its allowed and it doesn't really make sense to put our moral expectations and compass to drive the book because then there would be no story here. The reality of this world is that jumping is normalized and it exists so the concept of one's bodily consent is much less clear. So to rate the book 1 star because of it confuses me.

Overall I still enjoyed the book. 3.5 stars rounded up because I will probably read the next book as the cliffhanger was a bit insane.

Title: Happy Place
Author: Emily Henry
My Review:
You know for a book that has happy in the title I didn't expect to be crying so much.

I love all of Emily Henry's books and I haven't cried in any of them so when I started to sob at the 3/4 mark of this book it was a surprise, but a welcome one.

Even though the problem of this story and what it relies on for the plot is miscommunication, a trope I normally hate, I think it was done well. Because it wasn't just an isolated incident it was just who the character was as a person.

It's a bit strange why I loved this book so much when in all reality I really shouldn't, based off of the tropes. But, Emily Henry is just such a fantastic writer and is able to make you care so much about her characters.

My only real complaint that I didn't like was that Harriet didn't end up wanting to be a doctor or surgeon and instead just sorta became a house wife doing pottery that doesn't sell. And she was only able to do that because Wyn started making money. I didn't like that because it is so rare to have a breadwinning FFMC who is career driven and loves her career as much as she loves her man. That's what I liked a lot in Henry's previous book Book Lovers. But, yeah, I wish that when Harriet realized her issues and that she wanted Wyn that she could still have him and her career as a surgeon.

Title: Twisted Games (Twisted, #2)
Author: Ana Huang
My Review:
First venture into the Twisted series. I skipped the first book because it had lower reviews. I also am doing a buddy read/trade with my friend with another book in the series. So we are annotating and gifting to each other. I annotated this one for her.

I really liked this book a lot more than I expected myself to because the body guard trope is not a trope that I ever felt drawn too. I also generally have read too many Alpha male romances lately and a lot of the guys feel like they're the same. What made this book stand out to me was Bridget. I really liked her personality and her character development throughout the series. Rhys was like a plot device but she really was the main star.

Rhys himself is really not my type so I don't find myself attracted to him but he still got me to smile a couple times at his love for Bridget. I also really liked Huang's writing style in the book and her spicy scenes were well written and not overdone the way some of these other books can be.

I also genuinely enjoyed the main plot (outside of the romance) it was interesting. They mentioned Alex a couple times (The guy who's the main dude in book 1 of Twisted and he sounds a lot more my type so I might actually go and read the first Twisted book now even though it has lower ratings.)

Overall a solid 4 stars. I enjoyed it the whole way through, but it didn't have the punch to be 5 stars. No complaints but nothing stellar either.

Title: Remain Nameless
Author: HeyJude19
My Review:
This was really different than I thought it was going to be. What I usually gravitate toward (and what I expect for a Dramione fanfic) is really really toxic, horrible, enemies to lovers. With a huge emphasis on the hate part. Like I expect them to hurt each other emotionally and physically for like half of the fanfic. On top of that, I expect a lot of outside conflict and internal conflict.

While Hermione and Draco suffer from some nightmares and PTSD, and Draco suffered from addiction, the overall flow of this story is very peaceful and happy.

Because this fanfic has over 300k words, it's still quite a slow burn. But at 19/51 chapters Draco and Hermione are kinda together and there's never really a falling out afterward like I expected there to be to create drama. Thus making this fanfic just really wholesome and with a ton of happy feels and warmth.

Even in the beginning, there's no enemies because at the start, Draco is already a great person. He's not racist, and he's incredibly apologetic and nice. They kinda go from strangers to friends to lovers. Although I wouldn't have picked up this fanfic had I known that in the beginning, I'm glad that I didn't know that this was just a wholesome cute love story because it really just make me feel happy. Though, I definitely want to read something really toxic next.

Also, can I freaking mention one of the hottest lines (section?) in the whole book with Draco talking about dessert holy shit I was SCREAMING.

The story definitely had a much stronger beginning and I loved the development between the characters in the beginning. I'd say maybe parts 75-90% of the story were really dragged out and would've benefited but being cut or shortened.

Another thing that surprised me was how racist and frankly mean Narcissa was. I usually find that in these fanfics she tends to be supportive and not racist, but she was lowkey racist toward the end. I really wanted her to show up to their muggle wedding. :(

Overall, I really enjoyed how sweet and wholesome this fic was. I probably won't read it again, but I'm glad that I read it. :)

This book was really good! I was tempted to rate it 5 stars, but I didn't love it as much as I've heard others loved it. And I didn't cry. (I easily cry during sad stuff) I had a lot of expectations going into this book. But at the same time, because there was so much hype, I probably had expectations lowered. The writing and story were beautiful, and gosh dang it, I hope to one day have a love only 1% as beautiful as Patroclus and Achilles. The narration was just chefs kiss. When I started the novel I was actually disappointed to see it in first person. I haven't read a first person POV in a long time because I generally don't prefer them. But, it really was needed for this novel and I loved it. Especially at the end.

A fantastic book. Maybe now I'll actually read the Iliad/Homer like I should've in high school.

Title: Book Lovers
Author: Emily Henry
My Review:
more like a 4.5 star book, but rounding down to 4 stars because it didn't have the UMPH I needed for 5 stars.

Nora was such an interesting character because she's so different from other main character women, and that's the point. I also loved the tall women rep! 5 ft 11 inches lets go!!

The leading man, Charlie Lestra is pretty much perfection <3 I was swooning the whole time. Big fan.

My favorite part of this book, was although it was a romance, it puts heavy emphasis on the sister relationship between the main character and her younger, very different sister. It talked about the trauma from loosing their mom when they were young, and how it impacted their relationship. I loved the sisterly dynamics! It was really refreshing to have a 3rd character who is not the main two leads who is actually important to the storyline and adds something rather than just being background.

I personally couldn't relate much to the main character, but, I felt she was so similar to my older sister, who is tall, who lives in NYC and who is so similar to Nora.

The only thing I could slightly fault this book for was the miscommunication trope that created conflict. Not a favorite of mine.

Overall, great book!

Title: The Love Hypothesis
Author: Ali Hazelwood
My Review:
OMG THIS BOOK WAS SOOOOO CUTE <3

I wish I could live out my fake dating stem dreams with a hot prof. Instead all my profs are old men :(

This was so cute! I'm so glad I could finally read this book. As a women in stem myself (Computer Engineering (lowkey the field with the WORST female to male ratio of all stem)) I really resonated with Olive. I also want to pursue grad school (I'm a junior in undergrad rn) so I felt like this was something I could relate to even if I haven't gotten to that point in my academic career yet.

This book is highkey what I wish my future looked like. EXCEPT TOM. FUCKING TOM THAT BASTARD I HATE HIM SO MUCH. That situation ugh. It sucks that that shit happens all the time to women in stem. Thank god Adam is a real one <3. He's so perfect where do I find an Adam for myself?

Also as the resident pumpkin flavor everything lover can I appreciate that representation the most. Seriously I buy everything pumpkin flavored this fall, my roomates thing I have a problem. <3 olive and <3 adam and <3 and adam together

The only thing I was a little ehhhh about was that they kept mentioning that Olive was one of two girls of all the bio grad students at Stanford. And , yes, stem doesn't have much women in it, but biology is a pretty even field, if not more dominated by women. I checked out the stats myself, and at Stanford this past year, there are 92 Biology FEMALE Grad students and 82 Biology male grad students. This only ticked me off slightly because ECE is probably one of the field that women are most underrepresented in and I could only wish to have the ratios that biology has.

Title: The Secret History
Author: Donna Tartt
My Review:
This book was incredible. I don't have words right now to describe how I'm feeling. It's 2am. I couldn't stop reading when I got close to the end. I was in shock. I couldn't believe it.

This is one of the first books I've read in my life that was written for adults and is considered "literature" that I actually enjoyed. I thought it was so interesting how the book is set up. We know from the prologue that Bunny gets murdered, but we spend the rest of the books seeing how that occurred. I thought the writing was very beautiful.

I liked how the story was narrated.

I thought the characters did a bit too much drugs though, and in between wrapping up the Bunny situation, and the end it stalled for a bit before picking back up again and I couldn't put it down until I was done.

I'm really glad that I read this book right now, because I'm a junior in a northeast "prestigious" "liberal arts" college during late fall / early winter so it gave me hella vibes.

I wish there were more books like this.

Title: The Inheritance Games (The Inheritance Games, #1)
Author: Jennifer Lynn Barnes
Publisher: Little, Brown Books for Young Readers
My Review:
Oh, boy. This was a really great book. I don't have a real rhyme or reason on why I give this 4/5 instead of 5/5. Maybe, I'll just say its a 4.5/5.

I liked Avery. I liked her a lot from the very 2nd page when she said,
I had a habit of cutting things close. I walked the same tightrope with my grades: How little effort could I put in and still get an A? I wasn't lazy. I was practical.

I'm the same way... sadly, that's where the similarities between me and Avery end. Because, she is so much smarter, cooler, and stronger than I am.

The four Hawthorne brothers. Oh, what I could say about them. Let's start with the one I care least about:

Nash. Honestly, don't have much to say. He's whatever. Very side character. I don't see how he'll be important in the future yet, if at all. Next,

Xander. I like Xander, he's smart and nerdy and he just wants to feel included and be seen. I'm glad that he's the one with most of the information. I hope he doesn't stab Avery in the back though.

Now, how to talk about Jameson and Grayson separately? Personally, I like Grayson a lot more, so let's talk about Jameson first.

Jameson is so tricky, because I cannot tell what is going inside of his head. On the outside he seems so easy to read. He's hyper focused on the game, and he feels guilt toward Emily. He didn't really show real emotion toward Avery, at least not as far as we know. Then again, the story is written from her perspective. However, Grayson's line at the end of the novel.

"I will always protect you," he told me, his jaw tight, his eyes shadowed. "You deserve to feel safe in your own home. And I'll help you with the foundation. I'll teach you what you need to know to take to this life like you were born to it. But this.. us.." he swallowed. "It can't happen, Avery. I've see the way Jameson looks at you." He didn't say that he wouldn't let another girl come between them. He didn't have to.


I think it's very clear, that Grayson has feelings toward Avery. And, I think, in the beginning, Avery had more feelings toward Jameson, but now she's redirected them toward Grayson. I am a sucker for gray eyed color boys. Also, Grayson is just a cooler name than Jameson, so I'm more inclined to like him that way. Shallow? Yes. Do I care? No.

Oops, ended up talking more about Grayson than Jameson in the Jameson part. So, here, non-spoilery things. I like Grayson the best and also he's hot. I want him to be happy. Emily played both these boys like a fiddle, and I believe both of them were equally hurt and pained by her. Maybe Grayson, a bit more. I don't want him to be hurt again, but if Grayson likes Avery, why should he let Jameson have her? I don't know.

I'm really excited about the next book... I'm going to go pre-order it now. I'm kinda upset I have to wait, but it's only like a month and a half.

Title: In a Holidaze
Author: Christina Lauren
My Review:
I read this in one sitting in the middle of the night when I only wanted to read a couple chapters before sleeping. So, it was really easy to read and very addicting.

I loved reading this Christmas romance in the middle of August because I miss the winter vibes. I also didn't know it was going to take place in Park City. I lovee Park City, I lived there 7 months this past year, including the Christmas. I was totally trying to figure out all the places they were talking about, but I'm not sure all of them quite existed.... either way, that's fine, I'm sure they couldn't name actual places anyway for slander or copyright something another.

Anyway, that's besides the point, the book was really cute. Did the time travel/ Groundhog day thing make any sense? Nope, but you just have to believe in Christmas miracles and you'll be fine. At first, Andrew felt a bit fake like he was just so perfectly responding to Maisie the entire time, and I was like this is kinda sus, he's toooo perfect, but I guess it wasn't sus after all and he's just amazing.

These contemporary romance novels are going to be the death of me because I now have standards for men that will never be achieved by any living man on the planet haha.

Also, I loved Benny as a side character, he was honestly great. We all need a Benny in our lives.

My Review:
This might be one of the most conflicting ratings I've ever given. Id say up until 450 pages, I was ready to give this book like 1.5 stars, and be nice and round up to two stars. Then, the last 200 pages got interesting, and the last 100 pages were REALLy interesting.

I actually really enjoyed the last 1/5 of the book ALOT. There was action, and information, and so many exciting things happening. I wish this book was like 350 pages long, and the first 450 pages had been only 50 pages long. Seriously, the beginning was just nothingness. It was so beyond boring and repetitive and had no spice or plot at all. This book took me so fucking long to read because it took me weeks to read the first 450 pages, and then I read the rest of the pages in two days.

I think I'll have to continue the series because I want to know what happens but also if shit gets slow again, I'm gonna ax the series. I want to know, but I don't need to know.

Poppy's character is exactly what you'd expect of a female heroine in this genre of books. She's a badass fighter, she's stubborn and defensive. She's aggressive, and sexy. I wouldn't expect anything else.

Hawke is exactly like Rowan. I will make no further comments.

I also tabbed up and annotated this book like you cannot believe for my friend. I really am excited for her to read all my notes. I'm also proud, cuz I usually don't do that. I wish I could add a photo, but I've been trying forever and it keeps failing so sorry.

I should stop reading Dramione fanfiction but I can't. It's too good.

BUT THIS WAS SOOO GOOD.
The ending was just. Bittersweet... more bitter than sweet.
I'm crying.
Holy crap.

the fact that I feel Snape was killed as a plot device and there could've been so much more done with his storyline. That would be the only flaw that I could find in this novel.

also its def not just 700 ish pages long. More like, 1400.

EDIT 7/10/2021:

Hi, I just reread this fanfic starting with the flashbacks and thus reading the story chronologically. After I finished reading the flashbacks and had to read from the beginning of the story when Hermione didn't have her memories I was sobbing. I couldn't even read it. I got stuck on chapter 3 and had to take a break for a couple hours because it was too painful. I didn't really think I would be so affected by it but it was so emotional.

There really is no other fanfic like Manacled. It's truly a beast of a story in the best way and everything about the thoughtfulness and the tiny details that you miss in the first part, that you can only understand having read the flashbacks first meant that the reread was so different than the first time I read it, and equally as painful.

The ending is just as bittersweet. It's crazy how as I was rereading, I still had hope for all these things that I wanted to happen (in a much more happily ever after type beat) but even though I knew what was going to happen I still couldn't stop myself from hoping.

ALSO i LITERLALY GOT THIS FANFIC BINDED INTO 3 SEPERATE PAPERBACK BOOKS BUT THEY'RE LEFT IN A DIFFERENT HOME THAN WHERE i AM THIS WHOLE SUMMER SO I REREAD IT ON AO3 AGAIN.

oh well that just means that I get to reread it again in physical copy version later. See you in 6 months when I realize that all other dramione fanfics are just not good and come back to this one again.

Title: The Atlas Six (The Atlas, #1)
Author: Olivie Blake
My Review:
I tried really hard to love this book. Like really hard, and I just couldn't. I saw so many tiktoks saying that this was the most amazing book that they had read this year, that they had read this book 8 times, that people said it was life changing. So, I kinda had high expectations, but also didn't know what to expect.

All the top reviews are 5 stars. There are hardly any negative reviews.

As I started this book, I realized that the author used large vocabulary words and the writing was largely more complicated than your average YA book. So, I decided to google words I didn't know, and annotate the book. I read it slowly. I didn't skim. I wanted to give it the fairest shot possible so I could love it.

The premise was great.... the execution was... well what execution. As far as I can tell nothing really happened in this book. Sure, that's fine it's supposed to be super character driven... BUT I BARELY KNOW ANYTHING ABOUT ANY OF THE CHARACTERS.

I'm really confused, and I don't know what's going on with anyone or anything... but also it was fairly somehow interesting. I'm not sure I think it took me over 10 hours of reading and over a week to read. IDK I just don't know. Maybe I'll have to revisit this in the future, because I want so badly to love it and I just don't.

Title: Parachutes
Author: Kelly Yang
My Review:
So this book was interesting. The beginning had me a little bit irked. I felt as if the dynamics and writing of the characters of parachutes and ABC's and white students in LA high school didn't feel natural or realistic. I attributed this to the author's lack of going to a high school at high school age since she went to college at the age of 13.

However, as the book changed course into more serious topics of predatory sexual assault and rape, the story got more engaging and horrifying. I felt as if the writing improved and felt more real. Sadly. (Because obviously rape and sexual assault is bad but the writing was so much better.)

I read the author's note at the end and can understand why her writing felt more realistic. I really hope that in the alternate universe of this book that Clair and Dani really do get justice for what happened.

I also hope that to the girls that this actually happens to in real life that eventually in society girls who get assaulted and raped can seek help instead of feeling shame for something that was not their fault.

This book overall had a good message and went in a direction that I did not expect, but was glad that it did.

Title: Red, White & Royal Blue
Author: Casey McQuiston
My Review:
God this book was so fucking annoying. I really went into it with high hopes and wanting to love it so bad because it was supposed to be adorable and cute.

Instead what I got was the most annoying, selfish, arrogant, rude, privileged main character, Alex who could not shut up about how his life sucked so bad. Honestly, the amount of times he complained that being half mexican made him less privileged than the millions of white people despite being the FSOTUS was cringy af.

I would not want Alex to be a politician. Frankly, he gets drunk wasted every other night and is totally an alcoholic yet that's never mentioned.

Harry was alright, I actually kinda liked his character. But, since the story was told from Alex's point of view it was annoying af. Also, the amount of white savior democrats will save all the minorities was a little too fucking prevalent for this book to be enjoyable.

Quite frankly, McQuiston's writing was just low level and this read like a wattpad fanfic from middle school. I don't think I'll read another book by her again.

Title: The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue
Author: Victoria E. Schwab
My Review:
I am broken.

Sometimes I regret giving 5 stars to all these other books I've read recently and in the past because when I give this book 5 stars it means something entirely different. How this book destroyed me is entirely different. How this book exists is in a different space as all those other books.

The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue may be one of the best books I've read this year so far, if not one of the best books I've read ever.

This is the first V.E. Schwab book I've read and is definitely not the last. The writing was beautiful, the way that Schwab interlaced the past and the present was perfection. The way I got to understand the characters together was insanity. And the ending. (not a spoiler) but the ending. I thought of how the book could end as I was reading. Thought of so many different scenarios and endings... What I wanted to happen, how I thought it would end because there was no way Schwab could be so nice... it had to be cruel... Instead the ending was both everything I wanted and nothing I wanted. What I didn't expect until I did.

This book was beautiful throughout. I'm glad that I bought it in the spur of the moment and read it because I wasn't intending to read it, but I did.

Wow. Fantastic amazing novel. I need to wipe my tears now. Wow

Title: The Ivies
Author: Alexa Donne
My Review:
Now, I did go to a public school in California, not a boarding school in the north east, but my high school was really competitive for colleges so that is why I was originally interested in this book.

I never had aspirations for an Ivy league because I was never gonna be good enough, but I still had pressures to Early Decision to a private school. So, I did understand a lot of the feelings of all the kids on ED day in the first part of the book. I particularly loved the shout out to r/applyingtocollege because I would check that subreddit religiously throughout junior and senior year, even making a couple posts. (I'm currently a rising Junior in college c/o 2023). I'm so glad that college applications are in the past for me.

I loved the premise of the book and the way it was told. I did not predict the end at all. (I didn't even really realize it was technically a mystery when I first started reading the book.)

When the reason on why Tyler killed Emma comes to light in the end. (Literally so he has a good college essay) I was shocked but honestly it's not even as weirder than thinking Avery killed her for taking her spot at Harvard. I feel bad that Olivia got rescinded from Harvard while Ethan got to go. (Honestly fuck Ethan I really wanted him to be a nice sweet boy that Olivia was going to fall in love with but he is a major dick head) I'm glad Olivia got into Smith later after her forced gap year, but it's no Harvard. The ending is very bitter sweet. It isn't fair that the rest of the Ivies still got to go to good schools.



But, I was hooked and polished the book off in one sitting in a couple hours.
Genre: Thriller, young adult

Title: Throne of Glass (Throne of Glass, #1)
Author: Sarah J. Maas
My Review:
I finally bit the bullet to read this book after countless recommendations and owning the book for 5 years. And it was pretty enjoyable to read.

My youngerself would've enjoyed this book far more than I did but there were a bunch of little things that threw me off.

For one, the very beginning with descriptions of the characters. It was so laughable of how gorgeous she used to be. And ofc Dorian has those startling blue eyes and the "raven-black hair" like every other male lead in a YA romance.

There were some things that irked one; one being they always talk about how she is so terrifying, and murderous. How she did all these things in her past that proved her to be the BEST assassin, to have no heart. But, there is 0 proof in this entire novel. She doesn't do anything. Action speaks louder than words. Don't tell us that she is such a badass and give us no proof that she is. Also, I don't care if she was trained in extreme and horrible conditions from ages 8-14. She is an underweight skinny average height female who is 18. It would not be easy for her to beat a 250 pound 6ft+ super trained male solider.

In fact the one time she was shown to struggle, in the first test she can barely stay in the middle of the pack and throws up at the end. That's prob the only test she should have an advantage in. She's underweight but must have stamina from working in those conditions for a year. So she should be good at going a long distance of running. All those super muscley men should have it harder to lug their muscles for a long time. All long distance runners are lean as hell. I felt like there wasn't a lot of research in the book.

Despite my critiques, the book was still pretty enjoyable to read and that's why I gave it 3 stars. I still had a good time reading it and I want to continue with the series.

Another thing though, the romance with Dorian was like so weird? Like it was kinda insta lust because they never really spent time together. Though I liked him and was upset when she just broke things off with him at the end. And for what? Her reasons didn't make a lot of sense. But I suppose in order to have a love triangle they have to give Chaol a fighting shot in the next book.

Also, I really liked Nox's character I'm sad that he left he was pretty cool and I wish we could learn more about him.
Genre: No ISBN

Title: Renegades (Renegades, #1)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
The beginning half of the book was kinda slow, but I know that there needs to be world building. The story started to pick up around the half way mark and I really enjoyed the second half. The closer I got to the end, the better the book got, so I'm really excited for the next book.

The little bits of Nova and Adrian liking each other in the beginning were kinda cringe, well kinda cringe throughout the whole book, but it seems to be getting slightly more natural toward the end.

The set up of the story reminded me a lot of My Hero Academia with the quirks and stuff but it's a fairly common set up so I'm not that upset.

There's a few things I don't really understand. Like if Nova has been with the anarchists for her entire life and she's known to the outside world as Nightmare how was there no connection between her and the anarchists before the events that happened in this book?

I liked Ingrid's character more in the beginning but she seemed a little bit unstable.

I realize I'm only really complaining and critiquing the book and I still gave it 4 stars because even though I see a lot of problems with the book I still enjoyed it and enjoy Marissa Meyer's writing.

Title: Field Notes on Love
Author: Jennifer E. Smith
My Review:
Jennifer E. Smith knows how to write them. ("them" being super cute little romance contemporaries)

I was stupidly giggling throughout the entire book as I read it just laughing and smiling because it was just so cute and adorable. Then I'd look up at the wall and realize I was actually giggling out loud over a cute couple in a book that met less than 48 hours earlier while being alone and single in my bedroom at midnight. Despite the fact that I'm lonely af, I enjoyed myself vicariously through these characters. Though, that's not the only reason why I liked this book.

Even though the book is really short and takes place throughout a week, the characters have a lot of personality and depth that we discover and watch them have a lot of growth to find their independence throughout the novel. Both Mae and Hugo are incredibly likeable unique characters and I love them so much.

Near the end ever since the death of Nana I had tears streaming down my face. First sad tears, cuz Nana died and they had to split up but the tears kept streaming down my face all the way to the end even as it became happy and cute again.

I really loved this book and it was exactly what I needed to get out of this horrific reading slump as I dragged myself to finish [b:War Storm|27188596|War Storm (Red Queen, #4)|Victoria Aveyard|https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1510773212l/27188596._SY75_.jpg|47224720] since that was dreadfully boring and overally long.

I recommend this to anyone looking for a super short, cute, whimsical (if not slightly unrealistic, though in the best way), and amazing contemporary novel. :))

Title: Cruel and Beautiful World
Author: Lena Phoria
My Review:
I liked it and it was sweet. Especially Bronston <3. However, it just didn't live up to my expectations. The plot was weak as well as the Dramione aspect. I don't know why it's a cult classic Dramione fic. My emotions never felt destroyed and I didn't cry.

I also felt like a lot of characters just didn't make sense. So many death eaters defect and betray Voldemort. Why? We are really not given much explanation. Draco also says twice in the book that his idea on blood purity hasn't changed and he still believes purebloods are superior to muggle borns but that he just doesn't think muggle borns should be treated as slaves. Like okay? That was his view at the beginning and his view at the end.

Essentially, falling in love with Hermione did nothing to Draco's development as a character. He never changed, never grew. Even Hermione didn't really either, all she does is just get better mentally a bit and then forgive literally everyone who has hurt her.

The people who hurt her for YEARS all of a sudden just become better people for NO reason. Pansy just heals all of the scars she gave Hermione. Why? There's no way that would've happened. Also Lucius Malfoy at the end? What made him change? Literally nothing. What he did to Hermione was awful and horrible and it wasn't properly addressed how he just became a good person and why he was so readily forgiven. And worst of all, Rulphous's love toward Hermione. What the hell happened to him at the end there. It was like the author couldn't figure out how to get Hermione out of that situation so she decided to pull a super fast one and change his character so much. IDK I've read a lot of Dramione fanfics that were mind-blowing and amazing and this just wasn't one of them.

For being the longest fanfic I've ever read (Literally the length of half the entire Harry Potter original works) there was little to no character development and the plot was meh at best.

Title: Crooked Kingdom (Six of Crows, #2)
Author: Leigh Bardugo
My Review:
HOLY FREAKING CRAP I LOVED THIS BOOK SO MUCH

I don't have a favorite character, but I love everyone, and the plot and the twists and everything. I never knew what would happen!!!

This is very likely one of my top favorites series, and definitely the best duology I've read ever!

RECOMMEND 100%%

Reread in Jan 2019 and I've decided this is my favorite series of all time.

EDIT APRIL 18,2021:

(I actually listened to the audiobook with this reread and it was fantastic! I love the new dimension it gave to the story and cleared up so many pronunciation errors I had.)

Where do I even begin with this third reread? This book is incredible. It's hard to say if it's better than Six of Crows or not. Either way, it's no question that this duology is my favorite book series of all time, with the debate of my singular favorite book of all time being either this one or the first one. The character development in Kaz, Inej, Jesper, Wylan, and Matthias is incredible. I know I didn't name Nina, but I think she'll be getting more development in the King of Scars duology. Her character's arc in these two books is the weakest, but she's still amazing and I love Nina all the same.

The Matthias hate train needs to stop. Who who could hate him? That last chapter, 38, with him shows his incredible growth immensely. Even though it was my third reread, I still cried.

One of my favorite lines from this book is in the front half when Inej says to Kaz.

"He was going to break my legs," she said, her chin held high, the barest quaver in her voice. "Would you have come for me then, Kaz? When I couldn't scale a wall or walk a tightrope? When I wasn't the Wraith anymore?"
...
"I would come for you," he said, and when he saw the wary look she shot him, he said it again. "I would come for you. And if I couldn't walk, I'd crawl to you, and no matter how broken we were, we'd fight our way out together-knives drawn, pistols blazing. Because that's what we do. We never stop fighting."

That really broke me. It was the first time Kaz accepted that he cared. Really cared about Inej.

I could go on and on about all my favorite moments since I actually tabbed up this book (A rarity, I know) so I know where all my favorite moments are. But, I'm not so eloquent and don't want to accidently spoil something real.

I need to also give kudos to Jesper and Wylan. I actually find Jesper's character to be so unique because he's the only one of the Six that actually has a parent. A loving parent who's there with him. I just love how Bardugo is able to create such a diverse cast of characters in terms of culture, background, ability, weaknesses, talent, and personality. Yet, each one is just as rich as they are by the end of the novel.

I love this duology more than I can ever express and I hope to reread it again when Six of Crows book 3 comes out. :))

Title: American Panda
Author: Gloria Chao
Publisher: Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers
My Review:
This was an interesting story. Initially I was drawn to the book because I'm half Taiwanese myself and felt it would be a fun read. It was enjoyable to read.

I felt that Mei's parents were a bit like caricatures of every single tiger asian parent stereotype possible. And the character development for her mom, although progressive and nice to see, did feel a bit unrealistic.

I also wanted to love the romance, but Darren was absent for most of the book so I didn't really care that much. I liked her brother, Xing, and Esther's romance more.

Mei's character stuggled a lot and I felt she was written much better than the other characters. I just couldn't care about her passion for dance at all.

Overall I enjoyed the book but there just wasn't anything that special about it even though I wanted to love it so badly.

Title: Supernova (Renegades, #3)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
Holy Fucking Crap. Amazing.

This finale was incredible. The first two books kinda felt like world building and plot building but this book is where the shit happened. It had me hooked from the first couple pages and I read it through to finish it was 2am even though I had an early morning class.

The plot twists and turns fucked me up, man.

The deaths really made me sad. I didn't think that Callum was going to die. He just wanted everyone to have peace and be happy. Honey Bee's death was also shocking. Honestly, I was shocked where her character went. In the first two books the anarchists don't seem to be that villainous. But, they're also technically in retirement. We see everything from Nova's point of view and she's never known them during the war. She's only known them for after. Clearly, she hadn't expected them to be so terrible. And when Honey tried to murder Nova wtf. I'm glad Leroy was more reasonable.

THE FACT THAT ACE ANARCHY ACTUALLY KILLED NOVA'S FAMILY. Jeez. Her entire motivation for hating the Renegades was a lie.

And the epilogue where we get hinted that Magpie is probably Nova's little sister, Evie. Damn. Wish that would be confirmed.

What I really liked is that in this book, in the beginning the Renegades also gets villainized. They aren't the best organization. There isn't a clear good side and an evil side so we really sympathize with Nova's character as she remains conflicted to which side she should stay loyal to.

I'm really glad I stuck it out in the kinda slower first two books because this last book was 100% worth it.
Genre: Children's fiction, Science fiction, Adventure and adventurers, fiction, nyt:series-books=2019-11-24, New York Times bestseller

Title: Ruin and Rising (The Shadow and Bone Trilogy, #3)
Author: Leigh Bardugo
My Review:
I am crying. I just finished this book, and while the second one took me by STORM. This one RUINed me. get it?? NOW IS NOT THE TIME FOR PUNS, I KNOW

Anyways, this book gave me so many feels. I do not like the way the book was ended, but I believe it was the best way the book could have ended.

The beginning of the book in the dedication, it says that not all heroes are meant to live. Or something like that, and it terrified me on what I thought would happen. What did happen was worse than I could have imagined.


I CANNOT BELIEVE THE DARKLING DIED. I LOVED HIM.

FIRST I WAS LIKE. OMG NIKOLAI WHYYYYYY??? BECAUSE I LOVED HIM. AND THEN. AND THEN. MAL DIED. AND I WAS VERY SURPRISED BECAUSE I DIDN'T THINK IT WOULD HAPPEN, BUT I WAS HAPPY BECAUSE I DIDN'T REALLY LIKE HIM. BUT, THEN, THE DARKLING DIED AND I WAS LIKE HOW COULD ALL THE MALE CHARACTERS JUST DIE. BUT TURNS OUT THE ONLY ONE WHO ACTUALLY DIED WAS THE DARKLING AND HOW DID HE DIED FROM JUST A KNIFE??? WTF????

AND LIKE MAL AND ALINA GOT MARRIED AND HAD A NORMAL LIFE???


I-I-I JUST CANNOT PROCESS WHAT THIS BOOK IS DOING TO ME.

I will have to resort to fanfiction now for my shipping needs. Goodbye.

EDIT APRIL 7, 2021

I try to write my reread reviews before I read my old reviews in order not to influence myself with my old self. Honestly, this book is still good. I really enjoyed it. I didn't cry this time around, and I don't feel as if I was as attached as I was before, but it was still really good.

It was heartbreaking at some points. One of the best quotes is when the Darkling says: "I will strip away all that you know, all that you love, until you have no shelter but me." Yeah. I don't know why that makes me feel things. I shouldn't. The first time around I was undoubtfully in love with the Darkling from the beginning.

This time, it took me a while, I am older and more mature and felt his toxicity in the first book, but still he grew on me and by this book I was still shipping him and Alina. Moreso, I think the story would be so interesting if Alina did choose the darkling. I've never read a book about a main character who CHOOSES to go to the bad side. I hope someone writes an incredibly well written fanfiction one day where Alina chooses the Darkling either sometime in Siege and Storm or near the beginning of Ruin and Rising.

Anyway, I'm glad to have finished this. Onto Six of Crows before April 23rd when the Netflix show comes out.

Title: Today Tonight Tomorrow (Rowan & Neil, #1)
Author: Rachel Lynn Solomon
My Review:
THIS BOOK WAS SO CUTE. I really loved how the dialogue felt so natural and realistic. The character development, even though it only took place over one day felt so natural and not at all insta-lovey. Love the enemies to lovers ❤️

I really love how the characters felt like real people and not "perfect people." Rowan wasn't some skinny girl with soft brown hair and Niel wasn't some 6 ft hot guy. Rowan had a pear shaped body and not "western ideals" for her features because she had a bump on her nose. Niel was short. At 5'5" that makes him probably one of the shortest male love interests I have ever read about ever and he was a red head covered in freckles. They also, even being the top students in their grade, are going to NYU and Emerson which are both fantastic colleges but I'm glad they didn't both go to Harvard or Stanford or something.

The dynamics and writing just made me fall in love with the characters because even though they don't represent me, a half white half asian girl who's in stem, they did represent people who were normal and realistic. I'm glad that they had their flaws physically and personality wise and those flaws actually made me like them more.

Title: Stormbreaker (Alex Rider #1)
Author: Anthony Horowitz
My Review:
I first started reading this book series in 4th/5th grade and probably finished in 6th grade. That was around 10 years ago?

Now, I'm a sophmore in college and I decided I want to reread this series after watching the first season of the TV show Alex Rider on Amazon Prime. I didn't remember a lot about the series, but I did remember that they kinda skipped the first book in the TV show.

Stormbreaker is a good start to this series. I stand by rating it 4 stars as I did 5 years ago when I created my goodreads and rated this book by memory. If I read this book for the first time now, I'd probably feel more inclined to rate it 3 stars. There are a lot of unrealistic things about this book, but mainly that's just the premise and nothing can be faulted for that. I mean come on, Alex Rider is a 14 year old spy for MI6. What do you expect?

I still enjoyed reading the book and it was a fun read. It totally feels like an episode of Totally Spies with the gadgets that Smithers gives Alex and how they end up being useful later on in the book. It's a good start.

Also, I'm 19 now and I'm no where near as cool as Alex is at 14 in the first book ahaaha oh well that's to be expected. I remember reading this when I was a kid and assuming that I would be that cool when I became 14. Oh, how I would've disappointed my 10 year old self if she could see me now.

Anyway, long overdue tangent that isn't even part of a review... I will be continuing to read this series.

Title: Heir of Fire (Throne of Glass, #3)
Author: Sarah J. Maas
My Review:
About 3.5 stars.

Sarah J. Maas is not that good at writing the beginnings of books. Much like Crown of Midnight, the first half was quite a drawl and the second half picked up quite a bit. Though I do prefer books that get better as you read rather than books that get worse as you read.

Celeana's character still confuses me as I feel she is not one character. Actually the books quite feel like each one was written by a different author who had a grasp of each character slightly different and wrote them that way.

It took a while for anything to happen with her training with Rowan, who I disliked at first but he's growing on me as a character even if he reminds me of Edward Cullen mixed with Jacob. I also thought it was weird that he like NEEDED to be bonded to her by blood oath so quickly after escaping Maeve's like couldn't he wait an hour like think it through at all?? he's like a bazillion years old you think he's be smarter with impulsive decisions.

The witch girl chapters were a BORE I skimmed through them so fast because I just wanted to know what was happened to the other characters.

POOR DORIAN omg he like finally is loving this girl and being happy and she gets fucking AXED and he gets a fucking slave collar put on him omg no I feel so bad for him he's such a sweetheart and deserves so much better

Also like Chaol, I just don't like him. I don't dislike him either but he reminds me of Jason from PJO. Idk he's just kinda boring.

Then there's Aedion I didn't know what the think of his character in the first 3/4 of the book but he grew on me as well.

It's actually hard for me to rate this 3 or 4 stars. There was a lot I had problems with and thought were quite boring but I also really liked the end fight scene so I don't know if that makes up for it. I'll leave it as 4 stars for now but really its just in between.

Title: Queen of Shadows (Throne of Glass, #4)
Author: Sarah J. Maas
My Review:
Man, SJM, why are you so bad at writing the beginnings of your books. The first half of all of these novels are just far too long and boring. The set up before the action is very repetitive and I wish it would pick up.

The second half was so much better than the first half and I'm finally warming up to Manon's character.

Aedion and Rowan being territorial animals for Aelin is quite frankly uncomfortable. I dislike it a lot. The romance between her and Rowan also makes me uncomfortable.

Chaol... what happened to his character? He was kinda boring before, but at least he was consistent. It's like in this book his personality did a 180. I simply do not understand why he hated Aelin so much and why the entire time he thought she was a lying murderous bastard. Okay like to be fair she kinda is but that's my personal opinion. That was not Chaol's opinion.

Also, Aelin is like... her character is kinda confusing idk I'm not sure I like her.

I do like Lysandra a lot actually and the female friendship that she and Aelin had was refreshing.

Arobynn's death was just disappointing. His character is so talked about and put on a pedestal of how he is so cruel and amazing. Everyone is afraid of him including Aelin and the King. Yet, his death is so bland. After so much build up I really expected a grand fight, and Arobynn was supposed to win. He was so conniving and manipulative and I really wanted something more. He was so interesting too and now that he's gone its like meh.


Also, the king being a valg prince too wtf man.

tbh wtf is this whole book and series I always have so many issues and complain so much but like I still enjoyed it so that's why it's 3 stars. And I am too invested not to finish the series.

Title: Spin the Dawn (The Blood of Stars, #1)
Author: Elizabeth Lim
Publisher: Alfred A. Knopf Books for Young Readers
My Review:
4.5 stars

This book has me shaking right now, I am getting the 2nd book right away.

Even though I'm Chinese-American, I've never read a fantasy YA book based on Chinese culture. The premise and set up of this book was amazing, and I read it so quickly. I actually really appreciate that this is a YA book with a strong female character who is NOT a warrior (in the fighting sense). Usually in fantasy, the main character has powers that allow them to be amazing fighters, but there's none of that in this book and it was quite refreshing.

I really really love Edan and enjoyed the enemies to lovers trope a lot. Although, in the 2nd half it did get a bit too sappy sometimes. Maia and Edan were still super cute together and I ship it a lot :))

I thought Maia's character had a lot of development throughout the novel as she had more experiences and became stronger. However, I didn't feel as if Edan's character was as fleshed out as it could've been. Hopefully he gets more growth in the next book.

Title: The Tower of Nero (The Trials of Apollo, #5)
Author: Rick Riordan
My Review:
I'm going to be in college when this book comes out


EDIT: September 20, 2020

16 DAYS UNTIL THIS BOOK COMES OUT! I'm so excited!! 4 years later and I'm a struggling college sophmore. Hopefully this book makes me less stressed lol

Review (October 13, 2020):

I finally finished this book (although is finishing a book only like a week after it's released actually slow? anyway)

If I'm being honest this was not my favorite Percy Jackson / Heroes of Olympus / Trials of Apollo book. Do not get me wrong, I still rated it 5 stars and I loved it so much! I'm so happy that we were able to see more of Will and Nico together and I thought that the way that Rick Riordan ended this series was very satisfactory.

I love Apollo and Meg's dynamic of an older brother younger sister relationship. Apollo cares for her greatly and the way that Rick Riordan deals with the topic of an abusive and manipulative father is incredibly well done in a way that still makes it digestible for young children. Although I did not grow up in such a terrible home, Meg's own individual personality outside of what she had to go through reminds me so much of myself when I was 12.

As I read this series, I felt as if I was reading a character that represented my younger self, and when I was younger most characters I read about were people that I wanted to be. People that were so cool and amazing. But Meg is not a typical main character in a middle grade book and I just connected with her so much throughout the series. Not really sure where I was going with this... just wanted all my thoughts written down.

I feel like a piece of my childhood is dead though since there is no more after this.... (OR IS THEREEEEEE) like near the end Nico and Will's story line was clearly set up that they could have an entire series revolved around them. Like everyone else's story lines were wrapped up in a nice little bow except theirs. I would be soooo excited if we had a series on Nico and Will omg they're literally the CUTEST I love them so much.

I really enjoyed this book and it gave me so many feels. I'm sad to say that it's over. I grew up on these books and they made me love reading. How could it come to an end?

Genre: Magic, Children's stories, American, Greek Mythology, Juvenile fiction, Egyptian Mythology, Short stories, Monsters, nyt:childrens-middle-grade-hardcover=2016-04-24, New York Times bestseller, Children's fiction, Magic, fiction, Monsters, fiction

Title: The Burning Maze (The Trials of Apollo, #3)
Author: Rick Riordan
My Review:
I'm actually really shook. I finished this book last night and cried myself to sleep and this morning I'm still freaking out. It's actually been a really long time since I've felt this way about a book and I'm just so shocked.

When we met Piper and we found out that her and Jason had broken up, I was surprised, but happy that not every single OTP of kids at age 14 that got together, stayed together. I found it really realistic but I seriously thought that they would get back together by the end of the book. I had no doubts that they would fall back in love and kiss and be happy.

In addition, the prophecy saying that either Piper or Jason would die, I thought that was kinda fake. Like maybe for middle grade kids to think that someone would die but then nobody would REALLY die, like the word would mean something different. But, then, Jason did die. And in the most unspectacular way as well. I thought it was fake. Apollo's sarcastic narration made me not believe it until the end when Leo comes back and asks where Jason is and then I knew it was true and I started crying.

Jason was the first main character that Rick Riordan killed. In the OG PJO series, he killed many side character and those deaths hurt, but not that badly because nobody was main. And in the HOO series, I can't even remember anyone who died, even though I think most fans were expecting one of the 7 to die. I can't believe that Jason went through all of that. The great prophecy of the 7 literally defeating mother earth and to die in a book as a side character LESS THAN A YEAR LATER (in the book world) from a stupid fake not even a god.

I just never expected it. I didn't think it was possible and I'm really upset. If this was Rick's way of trying to get more fans to like Jason Grace, it probably worked. He was my least favorite character in HOO, like many other people. So he was probably the safest bet for killing. If piper had died, I think there would have been much more of a riot.


This book might be my favorite book in the PJO universe by far. The plot was interesting and complex. Apollo is a great narrator and Meg is seriously GROWING on me. I'm really glad I'm going to finish this series and close the childhood chapter in my life with a bang. This book made me feel emotions that I hadn't felt in a long time. Congrats Uncle Rick, you're still going strong. I was worried a bit during the Magnus Chase books. (I didn't like those) haha okay bye still so upset.

Title: Empire of Storms (Throne of Glass, #5)
Author: Sarah J. Maas
My Review:
I just finished this book 1 minutes ago so this might be super jumbled. Once again the beginning 200ish pages were boring af it took me 3 weeks to eat them. But, after that things picked up and I was able to finish the last 500 pages in two Days.

The cast of characters is larger now (and at times I feel it is too large. Especially toward the end) and I’ve really grown to like Manon a lot in this book. I also really like Dorian and Fenrys. (Fenrys is def my favorite "new" character in this novel.

Omg I’m so glad there’s no Chaol in this book cuz I dislike his character. So I’m not really looking forward to tower of dawn. Like I actually think this book is my favorite so far because Chaol was not in it. I feel like everyone really like Chaol but I seriously never did. But enough about him, he's not even in this book.

Omg the Rowan and Aelin sex scenes were soooo uncomfyyyy and also funny. The metaphors are hilarious and all the nibbling and biting is not it. Also just in general I'm super confused at the tone of this book vs the others. It seems that every single down time the characters have, or really any time they are not literally fighting, they're having sex now. While having these scenes in a book don't bother me, it does bother me that readers do not know what they are getting into. For the first 5 books in the series (I'm including the prequel") they have sorta mentioned it but it has never been this graphic. And for a book that is modeled for YA, I think it's not right. Since 13 year old kids can read 5 books and then get hit with this??? AND ON THE FUCKING BEACH are you kidding me. Sand gets everywhere. Everywhere. bruh just why.

Also the comment that Dorian makes about how it doesnt matter if manon is a witch as long as she has female genitalia its all the same??? dude not cool that was not a cool line. I've read other reviews and they think that Manon shouldve been gay and I def agree like the Dorian Manon thing is a little forced.


Lysandra is a beastttt (pun intended) I love her she’s awesome and I'm glad we were able to explore her character more. Her and Aedion. First of all why does every single slightly main character have to be paired up with someone. And throwing it out in 3 lines that Aedion is bisexual but then he's going to be with a girl anyway seemed lame. like SJM only put those lines in so she could claim she had diversity. But yeah why can't people just be independent and single. but...

along those lines, I do think that Lorcan and Elide are cutee. In the beginning I was lowkey super sus about it since I had always thought that Elide was a literal CHILD like I thought she was like 13 years old and when Lorcan said she was attractive and lookin at her amazing boobs i was like uhhh but turns out shes like 18/19 so i guess it's chill?

The ending was a little big rushed as they tried to set up the final book I think. But it seems pretty chill I guess. like near the end just bringing in all those desert ppl from the novella story and stuff like it was all too rushed and now we have SO MANY CHARACTERS it's a little hard to care about so many people because they're insignificant to me but then I feel like I'm supposed to care and I just dont.

I loved the scene with Maeve and the entire show down there it was the best part of the entire book. The way that Maeve is just absolutely cruel perfection. Except the thing about the releasing Lorcan and Aedion's dad from the blood oath like? I felt that was just plot magic like we needed stronger ppl on the Aelin gang so it was done under the guise of making them feel shame for all eternity or something but like its def a good thing so idk why she didnt just keep them as slaves or kill them. Anything for the plot to move in favor I guess.

ALSO ROWEN AND AELIN ARE MATES AND GOT MARRIED bruh okay dude i guess aelin is a genius who knew everything was gonna happen so she told lysandra that shed have to become aelin and shit and rowen needed to be married so he could be the air and Aelin just sacrificed herself like that and for what idk idk it was interesting i guess but I dont like it when we read all this boring ass shit of what characters are doing in real time and then later find out something craazy happened cuz Aelin is just a fucking genius. idk the writing is annoying at timessssss

Overall it started out slow and picked up. But even then, the middle parts were just so long. This book didn’t need to be 700 pages it could’ve easily been 450 and been just as complete and probably better in my opinion. I’m too invested in the story and I need to know the ending but thinking about reading 700 pages about Chaol makes me sad. And the final book being 1000 pages is a little intimidating. Hopefully I finish the series.

So you might ask with all my fucking ranting about everything that I dislike how is this book 4 stars????? BECAUSE IT STILL ENTERTAINS ME AND I AM INVESTED AND WANT TO KNOW WHAT HAPPENS IN THE ENDING DESPITE THE FACT THAT SO MUCH OF THE SERIES HAS ME WANTING TO QUITTTTTT.

no im not okay

Title: When Dimple Met Rishi (Dimple and Rishi, #1)
Author: Sandhya Menon
My Review:
This book was really enjoyable. I thought the author captured the asian bay area teenage vibe perfectly. I thought the characters were realistic and fun.

There are a lot of bad reviews for this book because they say that Dimple is a shitty person but honestly she seems incredibly realistic. Like, sure, she's "not like other girls" because she hates makeup and says some negative things about girls who wear super booty shorts or follow other humanities/arts stuff. However, it makes a lot of sense to me.

As a girl who was raised in a bay area asian household, I had a lot of the same types of expectations as Rishi. My parents raised me to only care about math grades and look at art/music/reading as purely hobbies. As well as makeup being a waste of time etc. I had a lot of negative thoughts on a lot of feminine things because I actually did have an inclination to stem subjects. I think that
Dimple having a little bit of internalized misogyny toward feminine things makes her character a well-rounded and realistic character. I think that makes the book better imo. I felt I could relate to her a lot and I understood a lot of what she was going through. I did wish they focused more on the coding aspect of the story, but the novel is a romance so it makes sense. Also, reading a story about coding is kinda boring cuz if I wanted to read about coding then why wouldn't I just code instead.

Anyway, I feel like the hate doesn't really make sense for this book. Another thing people say is that the romance is toxic because Dimple is super controlling to Rishi and doesn't let him have any input on the coding project or the dance. Which like totally makes sense. Rishi literally does NOT care about Insominia con at all. He went because he wanted to meet Dimple and was more than happy to leave because she wasn't interested. While Insomnia con is Dimple's dream. Ofc she can call all the shots?? like I really didn't see how that was toxic at all idk

Overall I just really enjoyed this book and it was nice reading a YA contemporary with a character that I could relate to.

Title: Crown of Midnight (Throne of Glass, #2)
Author: Sarah J. Maas
My Review:
This book was much better than the first and had some of the things I disliked about the first book fixed. Celeana is a badass. But her character is sometimes written to conflict that still. The first half was very reminent of the first book but it greatly improved throughout the novel. I enjoyed the 2nd half of the book a lot. Not quite a 5 star book perhaps 4.3 stars.

I don't particularly like Chaol I have to be honest I still like Dorian far more.

I was sad when Nehemia died because I really liked her character however I had been spoilt for it before by a tik tok. Also, I really liked how she killed Grave and later Archer. That was so fucking amazing. Tricking Archer like that and then him thinking that he was going to let her live before stabbing him. Beautiful. However, I wonder if she wasn't so infatuated with Chaol and Dorian by friendship would she have left Archer alive and such. What he was saying MADE sense. When she pretended to be on his side it MADE sense.

I feel this book's biggest flaw is writing an inconsistent main character. When Celeana is badass I love her character. I love that she finally inst afraid to kill. However, she sometimes slips back into that "quirky" I'm not like other girls because I eat loads of chocolate cake it it just doesn't make sense. I hope those inconsistencies in her character are fixed in the future. I want a badass and I understand they can be feminine and fall in love and have romance. But to be a carefree ditz is not in the job description.
