Title: The Dying of the Light (Skulduggery Pleasant, #9)
Author: Derek Landy
My Review:
EDIT July 25, 2020 Review:
Holy shit it's been literally exactly 5 years since I read the series and like i mentioned in some other before stuff I had totally forgotten everything. Everything at all so reading this book had me just as surprised and shocked as the first time I read it exactly 5 years ago.

I'm 19 years old now and I'm a college student, but this book had me sobbing just as hard as when I was 14. I literally took pauses near the end to scream because I couldn't believe what was happening. Sanguine's sacrifice for Tanith was my favorite and least favorite thing that happened. I loved him so much this time and he was one of my favorite characters maybe actually 2nd after Skulduggery. His story and personality was honestly amazing and I loved having a character who was clearly not good but still had redeeming qualities. He died for Tanith, the woman he loved, even though she didn't have any positive feelings to return to him. He was always one of the most selfish characters in the book but he really stepped up. He had the god killer dagger and he died with a triumphed smile on his face thinking he killed the black cleaver. Probably unpopular but his dead hurt far more than Ghastly's did. And when he died, Tanith felt something in her heart deep down and that hurt me really bad. Sanguine never even got to tell the real Tanith that he loved her. Because after she came back from her senses he respected and cared about her too much to tell her that they were fiances together and said they were just friends. It honestly hurts so much.


In addition the plan was just soooo good that they had come up with. I was sad that the Melamcholia died fighting with them and Solemon Wreath's death was so simple yet uneventful. Such big characters kicked the bucket so hard. I know some of them were implied to be dead like Dexter Vex but later he actually turns out to not be dead which is almost a shame. Derek Landy is one of the cruelest of authors.

And don't even get me started on Stephanie. Yeah she was kinda a little shit in the beginning when she tried to kill valkyrie and she did kill carol. But she developed actual feelings. Her relationship with Fletcher was a little weird I have to be honest. I feel so terrible for the dude though. First he dates Valkyrie and she becomes Darquesse and then he dates Stephanie who dies and BECOMES DARQUESSE. Honestly the trend might just be whoever he dates is terrible cuz REMEMBER HIS AUSTRALIAN GIRFRIEND WAS A FUCKING KILLER TOO holy shit the boy deserves such a good life. They would not have won so many battles if not for him.

ALSO I LOVE VALKYRIE'S CHARACTER! she is not some super good person who can't do anything difficult and hard. She killed her baby sister to get the septre (and yeah was able to bring her back but she didn't know that it would work) on top of that the septre didn't even end up being a super big deal in the final battle.

I love this book series with all my heart and it has hurt me in so many ways that I can't even describe. I now know that there is a continuation of the series and that it isn't the end but I have heard that it is not the best. I think I'll give it a shot with low expectations. I'm just worried that they might ruin my childhood and this amazing series that actually ended.

Skulduggery Pleasant 1-9 is my favorite book series of all time and I cannot fully describe how it has hurt me in the best way. I'm glad I was able to read such a work of masterpiece. I wish I could rate it higher than 5 stars.

I do disagree with what I said before which this is the best book in the series. The last 1/3 of the book may be the best section of the book written, however, my favorite book is book 8, the Last Stand of the Dead men. That book overall was just a tad bit better. I think book 9 had a slightly slow start.



ORIGINAL JULY 25, 2015 REVIEW:
I am currently crying into an every growing large pool of tears.

This book deserves a billion stars it was so good.

Derek Landy, you are cruel. Making us think that Skulduggery died and then switching back to the story about Danny, which was in the future, and then having Valkyrie joke about how he pushed Ravel into the accelerator. Pure evil as an author, but one of the best authors ever as well.

The last 70 pages of this book, I was constantly crying, a heavy flow of tears falling from my eyes. My heart is in shambles, and this probably makes no sense what so ever. But that is cool.

Sanguine. He was a good bad guy. The best bad guy. I loved his character so much. And when he died, for Tanith, by the black cleaver it was too much. I cannot believe it. Tanith then feels things deep in her heart when she sees his dead body, as if her heart can remember all the nice and loving things that Sanguine did for her when she had a remnant in her. She can't remember, but her heart sure does. She lost Ghastly and now Sanguine is gone too.

This is how I was feeling




There are so many things that I could talk about right now, but all the thoughts are running around in my brain, and I can't think straight.

This was in no way a happy ending. And the ending that Derek Landy made us think that was going on, was even worse. But I think that this was a "perfect" end to a nine book series. It was not a disappointment, and the best book in the series.

Why is there no more Skulduggery Pleasant???

WHAT WILL I DO WITH MY LIFE NOW?!

First things first, I need to stop crying. But I will never forget this story, which has become one of my favourite book series of all times, maybe even better than Harry Potter.



I hope I don't drown.

Title: Last Stand of Dead Men (Skulduggery Pleasant, #8)
Author: Derek Landy
My Review:
This book is by far the best so far in the whole series.

It deserves 6 stars!

And the next book is going to be better how?!?!

I don't understand how Derek Landy can be so cruel. He kills of characters all the time so I should be used to it. No. He went to far this time killing Ghastly How could he?!?!??! Seriously and with the betrayal of Ravel What even? There are THREE DEAD MEN LEFT!! and even then they aren't really together. This book had me screaming and yelling. I would stop reading look at the back cover and see "11+" How is this rated for an 11 year old? This book is full of gory death and bloody torture. I would close the book, bring it to my forehead and scream. There is pure madness going on during this book, and you are put right in the middle of it.

Valkyrie's reflection is good? bad? Who knows what anything is going on. The 9th and final book is scaring me. I see it on my shelf and I really want to read it, but at the same time I am terrified. Who will die next? What the hell is going to happen? Will I drown in a pool of agonized tears?

I want to know what happens so badly, but at the same time never want to pick up the next book. FEEEEEEEEELSSSSSSS!!!!!!!


EDIT JULY 12 2020!! I'm rereading this whole series and I always think its funny to read what i wrote 5 years ago when I was a totally younger person because I still agree with myself. This is by far the best book in the series so far and I was freaking out. The same things shocked me because although I knew Ghastly died from memory I had forgotten how and so the betray of ravel killing shudder and ghastly was just as surprising and shocking as when I read it five years ago. I still agree that I'm not sure that this should be rated for 11 year olds haha. The descriptions are far more gruesome in this book than previous and I love every second of it. This book series is entertaining to college age ppl too. Also, I'm still debating if I should continue after the 9th book (where I stopped before) because the 10-13 books dont have the best reviews and with this book being so good and I know the 9th one is awesome too, I'm not sure I want to ruin the world of skullduggery and ruin my childhood favorite book series. Pensive.

My Review:
I was actually going to rate this book 4 stars. The middle was a little slow and the scapegrace parts, in my opinion, were unnecessary. EDIT June 2020: I'm rereading this whole series and I'm enjoying it just as much as I did five years ago when I first read it. I do still agree with my past self that the scapegrace parts are boring and I wish the character died when he was a zombie but the alternate dimension stuff was fantastic. I love that Valkyrie is kinda not a good person. She's selfish and makes bad decisions because it and that's what makes her a realistic well written character in a totally fantasy setting.

Title: The Faceless Ones (Skulduggery Pleasant, #3)

My Review: OMG I love this series and this was the best one so far.  All the action and suspense, wow.  I can't believe that cliffhanger though, when Skulduggery fell into the hole.  I know they are going to get him out eventually, but this really means that Valkyrie is really going to have to do things on her own and not rely on Skulduggery any more.  I cannot wait to get my hands on the next book!

This book is supposed to be a romance story, and while that is true, there is so much more than just romance.

Title: Confessions of a High School Disaster (Chloe Snow's Diary, #1)
Author: Emma Chastain
My Review:
Short choppy sentences. Unconnected thoughts. Unrealistic thoughts. Somehow Chloe managed to feel both way too young for her age and way too old.

She laughs immaturely when she writes the words "Ice balls" for hail because she said the word balls. But, she's also a 14 year old girl who wants to get drunk and laid by the 18 year old senior. Her best friend who's ultra catholic and says the word "geez" instead of god. (They make a slip up late in the book where she says oh my god, but the characters don't say anything about it so idk) But, she does some pretty awful things about it so idk.

Also, Chloe is the worst friend ever. She can't respect anyone and constantly thinks she's better than everyone around her.

It's not 1 star because it was mildly entertaining by how bad it was.

Title: Heartless
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
3 Stars and rounded up simply because of the ending.

The characters had amazing development and change throughout the book, and I'm ecstatic that this was able to be published, and remain a standalone.

I did find the romance to be a little love at first sight/ unrealistic, but I liked both the characters enough, individually, to overlook that detail.

And, with the ending fresh in my mind, oh god, this ending. I cannot say more or I'm afraid I will spoil it.

Do you know how happy I am that the ending was not happy. No one had their dreams achieved. The ending was not righteous.

Jest died. Catherine went and became the Queen of Hearts we all know-mad. And the hatter ran out of time-mad.

There are hardly any stories where the characters fall deeper into a rabbit hole of darkness. Pardon the pun, but it suited my tastes wonderfully. Every time a book has an ending that's nice and, sure, it's nice, but it's never fully satisfactory. I always hope and hope that they turn evil. And Catherine finally did, and I'm so thankful.

Not sure everyone would be as delighted to read the ending as me. laughs maniacally

My Review:
As always, Kasie West has an amazing writing style and flow. I consumed this book like candy. However, the plot and characters were a different matter.

I usually love everything about all of Kasie West's books, and I previously loved all of her other six books, however, I was not that big a fan of this one. I couldn't connect with any of the characters and the situations all seemed too... perfectly planned out.

The main character was a complete push over, and the other characters walked all over her and it seemed to get worse as the story progressed. Dax didn't seem mysterious to me, rather flat and rude. Jeff was just too perfect, I honestly don't understand it.

The book was still highly entertaining. Just not a favorite.

Title: P.S. I Like You
Author: Kasie West
My Review:
This book, like all of Kasie's books, was absolutely wonderful.  I really wanted a book that I new would be cute and happy the whole time, and I'd been saving this book for until closer to the signing that I want to go to takes place. 

I couldn't stand reading something that would be sad, I just really wasn't in the mood for that.  Lily is unique and quirky, and she's easy to relate to. This book had me smiling and squealing so many times.  I just wanted the love interests to get together so badly.  Sure, it was a little cliche, but that's exactly what we need. Books now all try to be different with different tragedies, illnesses, and sexual preferences. (Not that I'm against those.) But it was really nice to finally read the classic girl vs boy, hate or love? Story again.  Plus, Kasie added her own twist and makes all the characters, even the side ones, have full personalities and barely any are cardboard cutouts.  I really enjoyed this book, I read it on an airplane in an hour it was fabulous.

Title: Front Lines (Front Lines, #1)
Author: Michael  Grant
My Review:
This book was damn good, but dragged out in a few places.

It was wonderful to be able to read a story where females were able to fight on the front lines.

I remember it was just a year ago, and my mother told me that females weren't allowed to be drafted. I was shocked. I had no idea the America was still so sexist. I asked why.
My mother said it was because it sucks when people hear 100 soldiers dead. But it's worse to hear 100 Women dead. I was perplexed. I told her, there was no difference in my eyes, and my mother said it was good to think that way, but most people don't.

This book showed racism and sexism that would have existed during that time and didn't go overboard with feminism. There are some things girls just can't be on equal footing with guys, like strength because of males simply have more testosterone. But, in terms of skill and intelligence, Grant portrayed a story in which not only did our main characters overcome the prejudice, they were damn good at being equal or even better in a few areas.

I recommend this book to anyone who's looking for a twist on World War II.

Title: In Real Life
Author: Jessica  Love
My Review:
I was very excited for this book and I bought it the day after I heard about it. Internet friends that turns into a relationship? it intrigued me because I spend lots of time on the internet and have friends of my own from there that live quite far away from me.

I read this book the day after I bought it, today, in 45 minutes on a plane ride. The words and story were candy, I couldn't stop reading, although I didn't have much else to do on the airplane.

I had quite a few problems with what the book teaches. The main character who is supposed to be a goody two shoes straight A student, ends up getting a fake ID, gambling and drinking to no end. In fact, all the minors drink until they are drunk in this book multiple times. AND THERE IS NO CONSEQUENCES! The author breezes over it and they barely have hangovers or any problems which result from drinking. If anything, it solves their problems. I hated the fact that an author would be promoting underage drinking in her book for young teenagers. It made be feel disgusted.

Other than the moral issues, I enjoyed the plot and cuteness of the other parts of the story.

Title: Memoirs of a Teenage Amnesiac
Author: Gabrielle Zevin
My Review:
First of all, I'd like to say that I think this book isn't for some people, so if you hate it, that's fine. However, I really enjoyed it. Except the ending needed to be like 25 pages longer to wrap everything up.

Gabrielle Zevin, in my opinion, has a really nice writing style. From the first page, it's just so easy to read and get into the story. I feel like I'm part of the story and all her characters are my characters. Everything just flows so nicely. The characters all feel real.

Let's talk about Naomi. I liked Naomi. Her personality and just the way she dealt with everything going on in her life. Yeah, there were a few decisions that I thought were stupid, but she dealt with the consequences quite realistically.

I like Will. He's quirky, passionate, and fun to read about. He has a clear goal, yearbook and I totally understand why he reacted the way he did. After all, Naomi was being a bit selfish.

James. I disliked James ever since it said he smoked. Smoking is a turn off and I didn't like him as the love interest the moment we got to know a little about him. Which is kind of ironic because one of his fears is that people will dislike him because of his past.

Ace was a typical jock, but nicer than expected near the end.

It was also interesting to read about the other side characters like Alice, Naomi's dad and mom, and Rosa Rivera. They all had such distinct personalities even though they didn't have to have one. I thought it was nice that all the characters were well rounded in this novel.

Title: Let the Sky Fall (Sky Fall, #1)
Author: Shannon Messenger
My Review:
Oh, how I wanted to love this book as much as the KOTLC series.

First of all, I'm being a bit nice on the rating. Realistically it should be two stars with the amount of unoriginal ideas there were in this story. But, the writing was still Shannon Messenger writing which is just so easy to read. Also, the material in which I believe the ideas were taken from is one of my favorite TV shows.

If you read my status updates, you'll see the YA cliche quote. Go ahead look, it's in every YA action romance. Once you see it, you'll never forget it.

Anyway, it might not have been clear, but I believe that this story was a complete rip off of Avatar the Last Airbender. A TV show from Nick that aired in 2005.

Some more summary, that is free of spoilers, of this book is that there are four winds. The South, West, North, and East. Quite some time ago, the North windwalkers murdered all the West windwalkers except for one. Vane Westerly. Audra is an Easterly and tells Vane he is the Last Westerly and only he can master all four languages and save the world. Each wind has a different language and the only one that is unknown is the Westerly language for the people would rather die than share it to the Nothern windwalkers.

Now, the concept of Avatar The Last Airbender. Instead of four languages it's the four elements: water, earth, fire and air. Aang is the last airbender because the firenation attacked and killed all the airbenders except him. Only Aang can master all four elements and save the world.

Both have the girl that helps the main character guy back into their world in which they left. Katara in ATLA and Audra in LTSF. Both strong female characters with romances with the main character guy.

Both have to defeat the leader that killed their people.

With lack of originality anywhere, I just can't enjoy this book as much as I'd like too. I will continue reading this series, but only because Shannon Messenger is one of my favorite authors.

2.5 Stars at the highest.

Title: Neverseen (Keeper of the Lost Cities, #4)
Author: Shannon Messenger
My Review:
Have you ever felt like you just want to curl up in a ball and die or just scream at the top of your lungs at anyone who approaches you? If you answered yes, then this book is right for you.

This book pulled at my heartstrings and kept my brain jumping around in anticipation the whole time, and even after it the book ended, because who doesn't like waiting a whole year after a cliffhanger?

Shannon Messenger is a goddess and devil at writing. (No offense intended.) What she has is both a gift and a curse, and I wish that it would be spread about more in the book community, because these books definitely need more recognition.

After book three, Everblaze, this series was on par with Harry Potter. After Neverseen, KOTLC has well surpassed it in my favorite series list.

So while, you're reading this and you might think I'm a calm person. (Well, probably not, but just go with it.) Just know that although I may look like a calm person on the outside, on the inside I am a mess of a person trying to cope with all the feels that are currently consuming my life.

Who cares about school or grades or work when you can shrivel down and cry while obsessing over fictional characters? (Just kidding, stay in school, you kids. (See what I did there?))

There is so much more that I would like to discuss with you, but right now I can barely write down any coherent thoughts in my mind. Although, Shannon Messenger, if you ever happen to read this, I have a few things to say.

Keefe.... Why..... How.... Prentice....ASDFGHJKL.... Thank you.

Title: The Isle of the Lost (Descendants, #1)
Author: Melissa de la Cruz
My Review:
This book gave me a new perspective on the villains of our childhood stories. It was an interesting and new take on fairy tales that made me feel intrigued. I wanted to know about Maleficent's daughter when I read the summary. Would she be the same as her mother or different? The way all of the descendants of villains were created, gave a fresh but nostalgic feeling. Overall the book answered some questions that I had always wondered, what happens to the villains after the "happily ever after" they certainly didn't get one, but I could have never guessed that they would be banished to an island.

This book was a very fun book for everyone out there who loves fairy tales. The plot is completely new and different, so it doesn't feel like it is a same old boring story. The movie is coming out and I cannot wait to watch it to find out what happens to the characters in the story.

You will meet the four main character, Mal-Maleficent's daughter an all around bad girl,Carlos-Cruella De Vil's son the nerd (he happens to be my favorite of all the characters), Jay-Jafar's son a thief who will take anything he can get his hands on, and Evie-the Evil Queen's (the one who poisoned Snow White) daughter and by far the nicest one in the group. Each character has a different personality that has individual depth and growth. And practically any Disney villain will be mentioned at least once. Your childhood questions will be answered in a fun laughable way.

I don't want to spoil anything yet, as I was given an advanced copy to review and the book has not come out yet.

Title: Trust Me, I'm Lying (Trust Me, #1)
Author: Mary Elizabeth Summer
My Review:
I am very disappointed.

I wanted to read this book for a very long time, and was bored and annoyed from the start.

Our main character continues to tell the reader what an amazing con artist she is, and how she never makes mistakes. In just a few pages, she is broken down and crying. She talks about how she can read people like a book, and ends up falling for the biggest cliche. Hot guy, who comes out of nowhere, has sudden interest. The girl falls in love and it turns out he was working for the enemy the whole time.

Not only that, but there is such a stupid love triangle. Best friend vs hot popular boy. Which the author can't even decide out how to make the girl choose one, and end up killing one of them off.

What's kind of disgusting is even after his death, while she is holding the hand of the other boy, she can't help but compare the feelings to the boy who is dead.

The mystery was okay. I wouldn't recommend this book to anyone.

I really liked the development of the world Oz. Danielle Paige takes the Oz that everyone already knows and puts a twist on it, describing all the horrors that go on in the now corrupt world.

I really liked Amy because she felt real. First thing she does when people tell her that she is the key to kill Dorothy, is asking if she can just go home and other people can do it instead. She doesn't magically become a hero and powerful, she trains and complains... a lot.

There were parts that were a bit boring, but that's mostly about the world building, it is a first in a trilogy.

I was going to rate this book a 5 star, but the ending fell a little flat for me, and just didn't seem very climactic.

I already have the second book and am looking forward to reading it.

BTW, this is a great halloween read!

Title: Zeroes (Zeroes #1)
Author: Scott Westerfeld
Publisher: Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers
My Review:
Holy crap this book was good. I can't believe how much I loved it. And the proof there is that even though this book is over 500 pages, I started it at noon during lunch and finished it now at 9:00 PM.

I absolutely could not stop reading. Everything was fast paced and intriguing. The characters were all so different and had past and personality that was interesting to learn about. Also, although the book takes place only during a couple weeks or so, there was so much character development and bonding.

All of these powers have their ups and downs, and it is definitely shown in the book the bad situations you can get in because of these powers, especially Scam or Ethan. (They're the same person) He has this voice which can take over, spilling information and the right words to get the receiver to listen and trust you, or... completely hate your guts. However, I still like his power the best and if I could have any powers in the book, it would probably be his. His chapters were also my favorite POV to read. Kelsie, aka Mob, was probably my least favorite character and chapters to read. I just didn't really connect with her and I felt like her power wasn't very interesting.

I also really liked Flicker, aka Riley, her power is also really cool, and if I had it, it would be great on tests. If, I myself wasn't blind anyway. Her relationship with Anonymous or omg I just forgot his real name, which is kind of ironic considering his power is basically you just forget everything about him, and the actions and words that were spoken with him. But, anyway, I thought his relationship with Flicker was really sweet, and I am so proud that Flicker spent the effort to make sure she would be able to remember him.

I'm a little iffy with the thought that Flicker's sister, Lily, might have a power too. Maybe with words and storytelling. But, it also could just be Flicker exaggerating.

I didn't really like Nate that much, I feel like if this book continued on as a series, Nate could become the main villain. I'm pretty sure he was supposed to be written as someone dependable, but Crash's POVs and thoughts really made me doubt him and his abilities. He literally could become the world's worst dictator with a power like that. Crash was very unique, and I liked how she really thought about the consequences and about real life. She was scared and she excepted the fact that she might not be a superhero. It was very different from the thoughts of the other characters.

I really liked the suspense and action that follow all the characters through the story. And the climax was very well written. However, the resolution, in my opinion, could of had a little work done on it.

Also, the plot was very complicated with many strands going everywhere, and it was great how everything connected in the end of the book. The bad guys were a little cardboard cut, but we got the hear little tidbits about their actual lives because of Scam. I thought that that was kind of cool.

And even though it might seem weird that I have some critical stuff to say about the book, yet I rated it 5 stars it's just because the book was just really that good, and you need to read it! There is always going to be flaws in a book, and I just happened to point them out, but overall, this might be one of my favorite books this year!

Title: Carry On (Simon Snow, #1)
Author: Rainbow Rowell
My Review:
I liked the story of Carry On.

However, I really hated the first 160 pages, I didn't like the writing, and the story was just so boring. I mean really boring. Or, at least, it was for me. The story started picking up when we got to the chapters written by Baz. Before then I was prepared to give this book 2 stars.

Except that I really liked the rest of the book. And the more I read after that... The more I liked it, and because 160 pages is only about 1/5 of the book, and I loved the last 4/5, this book is now a 3.8 star book.

Simon Snow is very boring and annoying for me, and everytime I read Agatha's chapters I wanted to stop reading. But, I love Baz and Penelope, they were amazing. I loved their characters very much.

I don't understand what Baz see's in Simon, but I ship them. I'm actually not even sure if the book made me ship them or something else, because I went into the book shipping them. I bet it was because of Fangirl.

Anyway, if you can push through the first 160 pages, I'm sure you'll love the book. If you're not one for slow beginning, then I don't think this is the book for you.

Title: Fairest (The Lunar Chronicles, #3.5)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
Fairest was not at all as I had been expecting. I really enjoyed the past that Levana went through. It showed that she wasn't just a heartless cardboard cutout villian. There was depth and reason, not matter how twisted, behind the reason why she was so evil.
And even if she was really evil, she still had a reason why she did all the things she did, to make sure Luna thrived.

We met the man whom Levana had always loved, no matter if he never loved her back. And when we found out that she was the one who commissioned the murder, I was suprised. But, also relieved. Does that make sense? Probably not, but I was happy that Levana finally realised that the man she loved was never going to loved her back. The actions that were then carried out... Well I'm sure there was probably a better way for them to be carried out

All in all, I really liked this short story, and the fact that we got to meet Winter before Winter the book. Which, I am very excited to read next month and meet Marissa Meyer at one of her tour stops. 800 pages of awesomeness here I come!

Title: We'll Never Be Apart
Author: Emiko Jean
My Review:
"I say the vow aloud, just to make it real. 'I'm coming for you Cellie. Come hell or high water. I'm going to find you. And when I do, I'm going to kill you.'"

It's too bad that this powerful vow turns out to mean nothing in the end.

There were some parts of the book in the middle that felt particularly slow and boring, but overall it was very interesting. The ending had a big twist that was very surprising.

The way the Alice dealt with all her issues and problems were very realistic, and exactly how a normal teenage girl in her position would act.

I didn't particularly have any sort of feelings for the love intrest, Chase, in the book. The author continued to build up the reason why he was at Savage Island in the first place, so when we actually found out, it wasn't very shocking.

Really glad that Alice realized that Jason was an idiot. I hate girl characters who just idolize their dead boyfriends and can never see the truth and their flaws.

Overall, a very average sort of book. Boring parts, interesting parts, slow parts, and a twist.

And incase you're wondering I ship sophie and keefe not sophie and fitz. Sorry.

Title: Never Always Sometimes
Author: Adi Alsaid
My Review:
The characters in this book had zero personality, and were about as deep as a kiddie pool.

On the first page we get this "If the lights ever went out in her presence, Dave was pretty sure the brightness of her eyes would be more useful than a flashlight."

I almost stopped reading right there and then.

Dave is obsessed with Julia to the point where it is annoying. But one party later, and after four years of being in love with Julia, he is in love with another girl. Oh wow.

Flirting and flirting later, Dave and the other girl, Gretchen, are dating. And surprisingly enough, right when Dave notices another girl, Julia realizes she is in love with him.

"She pictured Dave-her Dave, the funniest guy she knew, her best friend, the only person she could even imagine spending her days with-side by side with cookie-cutter Gretchen and her perfect blond waves and Julia broke into laughter so uncontrollable she had to lie down and let it tear through her. She ripped out a patch of grass and ripped the blades to shreds, throwing them in the air like confetti. As the bits of green rained down on her, she thought about waking up the guy on the couch and kissing him as an act of revenge, but settled on going to the kitchen to find more beer. Whether to drink or throw she hadn't yet decided.

Julia loved Dave. And she would tear her house apart to prove it.

A little insane considering she just figured out she loves him. And now when he is taken too.

Much later, Dave is now taking Gretchen to prom. Dave decided to go to San Fransisco with Julia. On the way back they end up making out on the beach, after skinny dipping, and having sex.

Dave in no way feels bad for cheating on Gretchen, who was already incredibly sad from her previous boyfriend that had cheated on her.

Gretchen catches them making out and they break up, and even though she is sad, she wants Dave to still be happy.

Julia and Dave right, happy ending?

Turns out Dave actually didn't love Julia. So they break it off after a day or two.
"She(Gretchen) broke the hug and took his hand in her, then leaned in to kiss him. It had only been a few weeks since they'd kissed, but the pause had felt eternal."
HAHAHA....

Dave goes running back to a waiting Gretchen, and Julia decided that maybe she likes Dave's older brother.

Julia and Dave remain friends. The end.

Thank god that's over.

Title: Second Chance Summer
Author: Morgan Matson
My Review:
This book started off so lighthearted and happy. I was laughing and shipping the characters, when all of a sudden,

Boom!

Everything starts to go downhill and you are sobbing your eyes out.
I was just sitting in my bed reading when
tears just start welling up in my eyes.

The characters in this book feel so real, and that is why I could connect to all of them so well. Taylor is a teenager, and she has all of these problems that normal teenagers have. What I liked so much about her character was that she was afraid of saying things. In so many other books, I find characters just spilling all their feelings and thoughts. Taylor was nervous, embarrassed, and unsure about what to say. She made mistakes, but wasn't annoying at all.

Henry is so cute. He was a little angry at first, which is totally understandable, but as Taylor and Henry start building up their friendship again from awkward meet ups to understanding each other's problems, they realise that their feelings for each other haven't really gone away. I thought that Morgan matson did an incredible job at their relationship.

Lucy started off so mean, and I thought I would hate her. But even though she was still angry at Taylor, when she noticed something wrong, she pushed down her feelings and tried to confort Taylor as a best friend. Which led to their friendship again.

Warren and Gelsey were two very quirky siblings which I thought were really funny and great. Warren and his trivia were just great. And Gelsey and her ballet. Perfect characters.

What I loved the most was the relationship that Taylor had with her father. People always take for granted the things they have around them. Taylor realises that she always loved her dad, but never really knew him for who he was. There are all these great father daughter moments, that I loved. And because of that, the last 50 pages of this book were like this
How am I supposed to deal with this?
I wasn't sobbing loudly, but I was making strangled breathing sounds because my sister asked annoyingly from the other room, "Why are you crying."

There were some parts near the end where I had so many tears in my eyes, and I couldn't even read the words on the page, they became so blurry.

I really loved this book, and if you didn't feel for the characters like I did, I am so sorry and shocked because I honestly don't know how you couldn't.

There was a slow beginning, but the book definitely speed up near the end, and I could not put it down. It was sort of refreshing reading a fantasy set in the 1500s rather than a dystopian or contemporary novel.

The main character definitely has flaws, but is strong and I really liked her.

George was really funny, thought he might have been a love interest, but once John was in the picture, I couldn't help but ship John and Elizabeth.

I wonder if Caleb is really dead or not.

This could have been a stand alone book, just with a sort of reader think of the rest of the story, but I am glad that there is another book coming out.

Title: Amy & Roger's Epic Detour
Author: Morgan Matson
Publisher: Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers
My Review:
This book was perfect. I read it in less than a day, because once I started I couldn't stop.

It was sweet, and even though it takes place in about a week or so, I honestly didn't feel that Amy's and Roger's relationship was rushed at all.

It would be so cool to have a sequel to this, but I also feel like keeping it alone would be fine as well. It wasn't a super tight ending, but it summed everything up without making the reader feel lost or cheated out of the story, with just the right amount of questions left.

I am glad that Amy and Charlie patched things up a bit.

I really like the photos, the playlist, and the little extra stuff added throughout the whole book, it really made you feel like you were taking the road trip with them, and I thought that was really cool.

Great book!

Title: The Darkest Minds (The Darkest Minds, #1)
Author: Alexandra Bracken
My Review:
This is unlike other popular dystopian novels. Okay, so the people can be sorted by color, but it's not really that simple. There isn't a bad side and a good side. There are multiple adult groups who are fighting against each other and the groups of children, who are more or less alone.

Ruby... What can I say about her? With no contact with boys for over 5 years, she seems to be pretty okay with handling them. And with an education of a 4th grader, she seems way too smart. Also, how can she remember so much history details from six years ago? I can barely remember the topics of this past school year. But, that was so minor, it didn't really affect me.

The story was so different, and creative. I really liked the side characters. How many oranges are left, how many reds are free? Why did some camps have yellows and others not. Why is the "resistance" so evil? I am looking forward to this book. I love it so much.

The author did a really good job of explaining the world and how it worked through Ruby, which I thought was fabulous. The romance between Ruby and Liam was a little forced, and I probably would have liked it much better if they remained friends in this book, and maybe in the next book, implicated a relationship. Because, even though they had feelings for each other, Ruby and Liam only acted on them because Clancy had tried to force himself on Ruby.

And even though most of this is kind of a complaint, I love the book as a whole too much.

Title: The Fill-In Boyfriend
Author: Kasie West
My Review:
This book was so adorable!!

Gia and Hayden are so perfect together. While reading this book, I laughed, smiled, sighed, and just stopped reading to stare into space and think about how cute they were together. Hayden, isn't perfect, which is great to read about. Not even close to being a jock, which is also great. Gia was very interesting. There was lots of character development that was wonderful.

Bec. She was probably my favourite character. She was very different, in the way that even though she dressed "goth and emo" brought out Gia's (the popular good girl) best qualities and made her a better person. Without breaking any laws or doing anything considered bad, she managed to pull off being a rebel character that allowed Gia to rebel as well.

This book was so freaking amazing, on par with Anna and the French Kiss if not better. Recommending this for anyone who likes cutsy contemporary that isn't just fluff as well. Kasie West really knows how to make her writing flow and write likeable characters. She also added in some real life problems in teenagers now, which was very interesting to read.

Oh, something I really really liked, was the fact that, unlike lots of YA contemporary, Gia and Hayden do not kiss the first time they meet. There was build up, with just a little bit of conflict, that made the impact of when they really did kiss so much bigger.

Love, love, this book, go read it now, you won't be disappointed.

Title: Mortal Danger (Immortal Game, #1)
Author: Ann Aguirre
My Review:
Shiz, this book was not what I was expecting.

3.4

Here is what I was expecting: Girl-ugly, unpopular, smart, gets bullied. Kind of goes down the tubes a little and obsesses over trying to get a faustian contract to get her revenge. Finding an old book or a webpage article, using a knife she draws a symbol on her arm. As the blood pours out, a demon arrives and basically becomes a Sebastian to a Ciel ( a Black Butler reference) but with a little more power. She becomes a little power crazy, and also the top dog at her school. Torturing a few of her enemies, she is feeling great. Yada yada yada. Things happen, she gets her revenge, and the demon is going to take her soul...but then falls in love. Or something to that extent. Not much heavy paranormal.

What I got was very different. There are monsters and a whole sick twisted game going on, and she happens to be a key player. As the book continues, it gets more twisted and creepy, with unexplained deaths that cause the main character to start going insane. She sees things in the mirror and across the street. She doesn't know who to trust or who she can talk to. Nothing is as it seems.

Although it was kinda confusing and boring at times. Some parts I don't think made any sense, but I guess these things can be explained in the nest book. I had no idea that this is going to be a trilogy, and I don't know if I will even read the second book.

I'm not going to lie to you, I chose this book because of the cover. And even now, this is probably in the top 10 if not the top 5 favourite covers I have on my shelves.

Also, they absolutely butchered book two's cover. They went from a cool, but simple infinity symbol bleeding with fancy font, To a cover with a girl's face on it... Seriously... why? Anyway, this was a really good book!
Genre: No ISBN

Title: Paper Towns
Author: John Green
My Review:
4.3 stars

This book was really fun and I really liked the side characters. I don't know why but Q just felt like an obsessive cutout for Margo.

The only other John Green book I have ever read was The fault in our Stars, and I hated it. Because of that, I was really reluctant to read any of his other books. But, because of the movie coming out in a week or so, I decided to give this book a try.

Paper Towns is definitely worth the read. It is fun and lighthearted, although from the beginning of the book, I kept thinking that Margo was going to commit suicide and was really relieve I wasn't going to be crying, when she was still alive. Although she is kind of a jerk. I mean Q spent so much time and energy trying to find her, and Margo just gives him crap when he finds her. Like, if you don't want anyone to find her, WHY THE HELL DID YOU LEAVE CLUES?!?! that was my biggest problem.

I found a few grammatical errors as well, but that didn't really matter to me. I just shaked my head and moved on, considering, I can barely write as well.

I really liked Ben and Radar. Especially on the road trip when Ben kept needing to pee. And Radar's omnictionary obsession. Really hilarious!

Title: City of Bones (The Mortal Instruments, #1)
Author: Cassandra Clare
My Review:
I kept hearing these terrible reviews like "The first book sucks, but you have to push through it and the second book because during the third book that's where the story really takes off." or "This book copies so many other stories, taking direct quotes out of them." and "The writing and grammar are awful."

Now, I have to be trueful here. The writing in this book was not the best. The changing POV's in the beginning were very difficult to understand. The grammar in this book also needs lots of work on. There was also one last chapter told in first POV of Luke, which was needed for the information, but could have been told in a different way.

However, I never really lose interest in books because they are copies of something else. Because if the something else was also something that I enjoyed, how can I not like the copy? Plus I didn't understand most of the references that the bad reviews were talking about. I guess that made this book easier on the plagiarism, if any was there.

I guess I am also one of the lucky few not to be bored the entire book. I thoroughly enjoyed the plot and the action, even if the grammar was a bit annoying. But, that was very easy to get over because I read a lot of fanfiction.

I am so very late on the bandwagon of The Mortal Instruments, but this summer I promised myself that I would binge read the entire series and the Infernal Devices.

So 5 stars for the story, but 1 star for the writing. I weigh these things very differently and the average became about a 3.7/3.8 review. I rounded up.

My Review: 4.5 stars.  This book was very inspiring.  I really really liked it, and I even met the author a week ago when I got the book early and signed.  She is really nice.  I feel like I should start writing my own feelings down on paper, but I know that I can't do that consistently, I have tried and failed again and again.  Now while I don't have a mental disorder like the main character Sam, I do have quite a few problems of my own.  This story makes me feel better and braver about myself, and I highly recommend this book.  There are all sorts of poems that are written in the book, and they are all wonderful.  I was a little ticked about the swimming part.  I am a competitive swimmer myself, and I feel like authors never can write swimming scenes correctly.  And even though it doesn't have anything to do with the main plot, I think that it is why this book is rated 4 stars instead of 5.

Title: Choker
Author: Elizabeth Woods
Publisher: Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers
My Review:
This story started off pretty bland. And before the last quarter of the book, I thought I was going to rate this book 2 stars. It had a good premise but it was very slow. The ending changed my mind because it was just so creepy and a totally different ending than I thought was going to happen.

What I thought: Cara is a loser. Her old friend comes and basically turns her into a popular girl and her long time crush Ethan becomes her boyfriend happy happy happy. But no... that is not what happens at all.

This book gets more twisted as it goes on and the last couple of chapters where everything is solved and falls together is not at all what it seems. So, a slow book to start, but with a really good ending. I hate writing spoilers so.... go read it if you want to know what happens.

Title: Hello, I Love You
Author: Katie M. Stout
My Review:
When I got this as a first reads book on Goodreads, I was really excited. However, this book is a real disappointment. The main character Grace, moves to Korea for senior year to run away from family drama and problems. Upon getting there she is immediate friends with her roommate Sophie. Sophie introduces her to her twin brother Jason. We know right after that Jason is the love interest even if he is a jerk and she "hates" him.

Jason has no personality. He is constantly changing as if the author didn't know what type of boy she wanted to write about and it makes him seem really bipolar. Grace is one of those annoying main characters who is extremely stupid. Not in the way of academics, she likes to recite the periodic table of elements when she is stressed and sad. She doesn't know how to speak Korean, but doesn't bother to try and learn any of it until Jason offers to tutor her. Her family, excluding her younger sister, is racist. Even though Grace moved to Korea for her own account, she doesn't want to try anything new. "A snicker escapes my lips. KPOP. Heh." She doesn't need to think it is funny.

The love story is so fake. The author tried to make it seem more realistic by making them dislike each other first, but it just doesn't work. And obviously in the end, they both confess their undying love for each other and live happily ever after. But not before, she confesses the major family problems and hardships of her older brother's suicide, which of course she blamed herself for.

All in all, this book was flat, boring, and annoying. I had to force myself to finish it and I am not really sure why. Don't waste your time.

The book was very easy to get into and fascinated me the whole way.

Title: Stargirl (Stargirl, #1)
Author: Jerry Spinelli
My Review: I read this book in class for learning about nonconformity.  I usually end up enjoying class read books, like The Outsiders and Touching Spirit Bear, but this book was not good.  The relationship that Stargirl and Leo had was unbelievable.  Leo has never really talked to Stargirl ever in his life, when Stargirl sends him a letter that says, "I love you."  All of a sudden, Leo falls head over heels for this girl and they immediately become like boyfriend and girlfriend.  A girl who always seems to know about people's birthdays and brings her rat to school everyday, who you barely know, sends you a letter that says that she loves you. If that happened to me, I would freak out and most likely call the cops.  Then, Leo, who does not want to be shunned by the rest of his classmates, stops seeing Stargirl.  And right when he finally starts to accept Stargirl for who she is again, she freaking moves to another state.  15 years in the future, Leo has never talked to Stargirl for any of that time, and she send him a present for his birthday, then the story ends.  The relationship that was built up, was worse than Twilight, and the ending was just stupid.

Title: Surviving High School
Author: M. Doty
My Review: I picked out this book because I am a swimmer and I have an older sister who always managed to get a better time than I did.  The book started out okay, with the main character training hard for swimming and working hard for school.  What I did not like was that this main character throws away everything she has worked for, for a guy.  A boy that she met literally a few weeks ago.  What is that supposed to show people?  And then and the last moment she rushes to Junior Nationals and breaks the record for an event, when she hasn't trained in a few days.  You absolutely cannot write a book that shows if you stop caring and go run after a boy, you will do better than when you worked hard.  I just simply did not enjoy the plot and how stupid the main character was.  But, if you do enjoy fluff like this, go ahead and read on.

Title: The Fault in Our Stars
Author: John Green
My Review: I know I am probably one of the only people who don't love tfios, but I didn't think the book is all that good.  Reason 1: I did not think that the book was realistic.  Now I know what you are thinking, "Cancer is real!  Why are you so insensitive?"  I am well aware that cancer is very real, I just think that their relationship escalated way to fast.  Also, the characters just seemed to perfect.  I am not talking about their health, but their personalities.  Augustus Waters and his whole cigarette thing but it doesn't kill him,  I mean what kind of teenager actually thinks about stuff like that.  In all, even though the main plot is realistic, it just did not give me the feel to fall in love with the characters and feel sad when they died.  The book just did not have an effect on me like it did others.
